35. f(x) = 2x + 3, g(x) = x - 2

a. $f+g = 3x + 1, D: (-\infty, \infty), R: (-\infty, \infty)$
b. $f-g = x + 5, D: (-\infty, \infty), R: (-\infty, \infty)$
c. $f\cdotg = 2x^2 -x - 6, D: (-\infty,\infty), R: (-6.25, \infty)$
d. $f/g = \\frac{2x+3}{x-2}, D: x \neq 2, R: y \neq 2$
e. $f \circ g = 2(x-2) + 3 = 2x - 1, D: \mathbb{R}, R: \mathbb{R}$

37. $f(x) = x^2 + 7, g(x) = 3x - 2$

a. $f+g = x^2 + 3x + 5, D: (-\infty, \infty), R: (2.75, \infty)$
b. $f-g = x^2 - 3x + 9$
c. $f\cdotg = 3x^3 - 2x^2 + 21x - 14$
d. $f/g = \\frac{x^2 + 7}{3x-2}, D: x \neq 2/3, R: (-\infty, \infty)$

49. $f(x) = \sqrt{x+3}, g(x) = 2x-5 $

a. $f \circ g = \sqrt{2x-2}, D: x \geq 1$
b. $g \circ f = 2\sqrt{x+3} - 5, D: x \geq -3$


1. From the book, Section 2.8: #35, 37, 49, 51, 55, 59, 61, 71, 89

